# When It Comes Together

In late 2025, I was consulting for two emerging venture capital firms preparing to fundraise. Both needed investment memorandums for their datarooms — materials that institutional capital providers expect to see before committing funds. One firm needed roughly a dozen memos on existing portfolio companies. The other needed similar materials on twenty portfolio companies plus polished write-ups on eleven pipeline companies, presentable enough to share with prospective investors. In total, I faced over forty investment memorandums, many on companies outside my direct area of expertise, with fundraising timelines that left no room for delay.

Writing investment memos is work I know well. A strong memo typically runs six to fifteen pages: company overview, market context, competitive landscape, financial profile, and an investment thesis. Done manually with proper research, one memo takes a full working day. Forty memos meant over eight weeks of heads-down writing — time neither I nor my clients had. I had to make a judgment call about how to deliver.

The conventional path was clear: grind through them one by one. It was slow and exhausting, but predictable. I knew I could produce quality work this way because I had done it before. The second option was to use off-the-shelf AI tools — paste in some notes, prompt a large language model, and clean up the output. I tested this approach and found the results too generic. The memos lacked the structural rigor and sourced detail that sophisticated capital providers expect. They read like what they were: AI drafts with a human coat of paint.

The third option was the riskiest: build a custom system that could orchestrate multiple AI models through a structured workflow — one agent to research, another to draft and edit, another to coordinate — producing memos that met a professional standard with citations, formatted footnotes, and integrated visuals from company materials. This is the path I chose, and it was a judgment call rather than an analytical one because I had no reliable basis for predicting whether it would work or how long it would take to build.

My hesitation was well-founded. Throughout 2025, I had accumulated a trail of failed attempts at building software tools powered by AI. I had built prototype applications on no-code platforms and watched them overwrite their own progress when managed poorly. I had written automation scripts to maintain data quality across files, only to introduce new errors worse than the ones I was fixing. I had built a system to watch my file directories and generate templates automatically, only to spend days debugging cascading failures that silently corrupted files before I noticed. Each attempt had a sound rationale and produced negative results. The pattern was discouraging enough that any reasonable analysis of my track record would have argued against trying again.

But a different pattern was also forming beneath the failures. Each dead end taught me something concrete about how AI tools break down and where they work reliably. I learned that AI is most effective when constrained to specific, well-defined tasks rather than given broad, ambiguous instructions. I learned that breaking complex workflows into small, isolated steps — each with clear inputs and outputs — produces far more reliable results than asking a single tool to do everything. And I had spent months converting all of my working files into open, plain-text formats that AI models process natively, which meant I had a clean foundation to build on. None of these lessons came from analysis or planning. They came from stubborn repetition and paying attention to what went wrong.

This accumulated intuition is what made the judgment call possible. I decided to build what I called an investment memo orchestrator: a system that used one AI model as a research agent, another as a drafting and editing agent, and a third as the coordinator managing the workflow between them. I chose a framework designed for exactly this kind of multi-agent coordination, and I used AI-assisted coding tools to help me build it. The specification and architecture took two days. Within five days, the system could produce a six-to-fifteen-page investment memo in under ten minutes, complete with sourced citations, formatted footnotes, and key visuals pulled from company slide decks. After another week of refinement, I added the ability to ingest any company materials as a primary source and export the final output as a branded PDF using custom templates.

The work that had taken me a full day now took fifteen minutes. I delivered all forty-plus memos within the timeframe my clients needed, at a quality level that held up to investor scrutiny. The two firms were able to proceed with their fundraising processes on schedule.

What made this judgment call defensible was not confidence — it was pattern recognition built from a year of disciplined failure. I had no spreadsheet or model that said "build this system and it will work." I had a accumulation of hard-won knowledge about where AI tools succeed and fail, a body of prior work that created the right preconditions, and a willingness to bet on that accumulated understanding when the alternatives were either too slow or too shallow. The decision could not be analyzed beforehand, but it was not made blindly. It was made by someone who had been paying close attention for a long time, and who recognized that the pieces had finally come together.